=====Usage notes=====
* The verb {{lang|ja|する}} (“to do”) is seldom written in kanji ({{ja-l|為る}}).
* It is common to use {{lang|ja|する}} after certain nouns to indicate that the noun is being done; this is ''highly'' [[productive]], meaning many nouns can be used as verbs in this way. Some examples are:
** {{m|ja|勉強|tr=benkyō||studying}} → {{lang|ja|勉強'''する'''}} (''benkyō '''suru''''', “to do studying” → “to study”)
** {{m|ja|旅行|tr=ryokō||journey}} → {{lang|ja|旅行'''する'''}} (''ryokō '''suru''''', “to do journey” → “to travel”)
** {{m|ja|アップロード|tr=appurōdo||upload}} → {{lang|ja|アップロード'''する'''}} (''appurōdo '''suru''''', “to do uploading” → “to upload”)
: Most verbal nouns are Sino-Japanese words (usually two-kanji), but some are of native ({{m|ja|和語|tr=wago}}) or foreign origin ({{m|ja|外来語|tr=gairaigo}}). Most verbal nouns can be separated from the ending {{m|ja|する|tr=suru}} by inserting {{m|ja|を|tr=o|pos=object particle}}; in addition to {{m|ja|[[日本語]]を[[勉強]]する|tr=Nihongo o benkyō suru|t=to study Japanese}} you can say {{m|ja|[[日本語]]の[[勉強]]をする|tr=Nihongo no benkyō o suru|t=to do the studying of Japanese}}. (You cannot say *{{m|ja|[[日本語]]を[[勉強]]をする|tr=Nihongo o benkyō o suru|lit=to [do studying]<sub>verb</sub> Japanese}}, despite Korean {{m|ko|^[[일본어]][[-를]] [[공부]][[-를]] [[하다]]}}. Modern Japanese cannot have multiple direct objects.) However, some verbal nouns are bound to the ending {{m|ja|する|tr=suru}} and treated as single words in dictionaries:
:* Sino-Japanese (usually one-kanji): {{m|ja|関する|tr=kansuru|t=to [[concern]]}}, from {{m|ja|関|tr=kan|t=[[relation]], [[connection]]}}
:* Native: {{m|ja|私する|tr=watakushisuru|t=to [[appropriate]], to [[privatize]]}}, from {{m|ja|私|tr=watakushi|t=[[private]] [[matter]]}}
:Such verbs can be thought of as morphologically instead of syntactically derived. Sometimes further shape changes may take place:
:* For some verbs the {{m|ja|する|tr=suru}} optionally changes to {{m|ja|す|tr=su}}, with type 1 (godan) conjugation: {{m|ja|訳する|tr=yakusuru|t=to [[translate]]}} usually appears in the shape {{m|ja|訳す|tr=yakusu}} and favors the forms {{m|ja|訳さない|tr=yakusanai}} over {{m|ja|訳しない|tr=yakushinai}}, {{m|ja|訳そう|tr=yakusō}} over {{m|ja|訳しよう|tr=yakushiyō}}, etc.
:* For some verbs the {{m|ja|する|tr=suru}} is voiced as {{m|ja|ずる|tr=zuru}}, then optionally changes to {{m|ja|じる|tr=jiru}} with type 2 (ichidan) conjugation: {{m|ja|感ずる|tr=kanzuru}} → {{m|ja|感じる|tr=kanjiru|t=to [[feel]]}}, {{m|ja|信ずる|tr=shinzuru}} → {{m|ja|信じる|tr=shinjiru|t=to [[believe]]}}. When they are not changed to type 2 conjugation, they make passive and causative forms ending in ''-zerareru''/''-zesaseru'': the passive form of “to believe” is {{m|ja|信ぜられる|tr=shinzerareru}} if not {{m|ja|信じられる|tr=shinjirareru}}, but never *{{m|ja|[[信]][[される|ざれる]]|tr=shinzareru}}. Most of these are derived from single Sino-Japanese kanji ending in a nasal (''-m, -n, -ng'') in Middle Chinese, but not all kanji ending in a nasal in Middle Chinese voice the following {{m|ja|する|tr=suru}} to {{m|ja|ずる|tr=zuru}}; compare {{m|ja|感ずる|tr=kanzuru}} → {{m|ja|感じる|tr=kanjiru|t=to [[feel]]}} with {{m|ja|関する|tr=kansuru|t=to [[concern]]}}. Furthermore, the voicing also occurs for some kanji whose Japanese reading ends in a long sound erroneously traced back to Middle Chinese ''-ng'': {{m|ja|報ずる|tr=hōzuru}} → {{m|ja|報じる|tr=hōjiru|t=to [[report]]}}, {{m|ja|投ずる|tr=tōzuru}} → {{m|ja|投じる|tr=tōjiru|t=to [[throw]]}}, as well as some native stems: {{m|ja|重んずる|tr=omonzuru}} → {{m|ja|重んじる|tr=omonjiru|t=to [[hold]] in [[high]] [[esteem]]}}, {{m|ja|甘んずる|tr=amanzuru}} → {{m|ja|甘んじる|tr=amanjiru|t=to [[content]] oneself with}}, etc.
<!-- TODO: kanji ending in a sokuon + suru, like 罰する and 察する, also favor ～せられる over ～される. -->
* The potential form of {{m|ja|する|tr=suru}} is the suppletive verb {{m|ja|できる|tr=dekiru}}. Verbal nouns that are not bound to the {{m|ja|する|tr=suru}} can form potential forms by changing the {{m|ja|する|tr=suru}} to {{m|ja|できる|tr=dekiru}} directly: {{m|ja|[[理解]][[できる]]|tr=rikai dekiru|t=to be able to understand}}.
* In headlines and enumeration of events, the ending {{m|ja|する|tr=suru}} can be dropped, leaving the verbal noun at the end of the sentence provided that it is not bound:
*: {{ja-usex-inline|午後２時に'''到着'''。|^ごご にじ に '''とうちゃく'''。|Arrived at 2 PM.|ref=[http://cjn-koga.life.coocan.jp/index.html]}}

* See also [[:Category:Japanese suru verbs]].

